h.'' [[Toronto Star]]. Monday, January 7, 1991. Page: A06.</ref><ref>-----. ''TORONTO IN BRIEF. Church blaze probed.'' The Globe & Mail. Toronto, Ontario, Canada. Jan 7, 1991. Page: A6.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The building itself houses:\n* The Youth Centre \"Megas Alexandros\"\n* The offices for the Church\n* Offices for the Greek Community Social Services\n* Offices for Olympic Flame Soccer club\n* A multi-purpose room\n* The Church, with a seating capacity of 450, and room to accommodate an additional 400 people on major feast days.|group=note}}</small>\n:* <small>A group of ten Russian Orthodox icon painters were responsible for the art in the rebuilt church.<ref>''[http://www.greekcommunity.org/ViewSiteContent.aspx/St_John Saint John].'' Greek Community of Toronto. Retrieved: 2013-06-20.</ref></small>\n| [[File:St. John the Baptist Greek Orthodox Church, Toronto.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| Metamorphosis Greek Orthodox Church \n| [[East Danforth]]\n| 1985\n|\n* <small>1923-1925 ''Donlands Methodist Church.''<ref name=Donlands>''[http://www.archeion.ca/donlands-united-church-toronto-ont;isaar Donlands United Church (Toronto, Ont.)].'' Archeion (Ontario's Archival Information Network). Retrieved: 2013-06-20.</ref>{{#tag:ref| United Church, located at 40 Donlands Avenue in Toronto, was established in 1925, formerly Methodist. It began a portable mission at Langford and Danforth Avenues in 1914. The church relocated to corner of Donlands Avenue and Strathmore Blvd. in 1923. It joined the United Church of Canada in 1925. In 1984 it amalgamated with Eastminster United Church in the Eastminster building.<ref>''[https://www.archeion.ca/donlands-united-church-toronto-ont-fonds Fonds F1440 - Donlands United Church (Toronto, Ont.) fonds].'' Archeion (Ontario's Archival Information Network). Retrieved: 2020-02-07.</ref>|group=note}}</small>\n* <small>1925-1984 ''Donlands United Church.''<ref name=Donlands/></small>\n* <small>1985 Metamorphosis Greek Orthodox Church is founded, August 20.</small>\n| [[File:Metamorphosis Greek Orthodox Community.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. John the Theologian Greek Orthodox Church\n| [[Thorncliffe Park]]\n| 1998\n| \n* <small>Toronto Orthodox Theological Academy</small>\n|\n|-\n| Lifegiving Font Greek Orthodox Chapel\n| [[Thorncliffe Park]]\n| 1998\n|\n* <small>'''Chapel''' - Toronto Orthodox Theological Academy.</small>\n|\n|-\n| Sts. Anargyroi Hellenic Home Chapel \n| [[Bracondale Hill]]\n|\n|\n* <small>'''Chapel''' - Old Age Home</small>\n|\n|-\n| Sts. Cyril and Methodios Hellenic Home Chapel\n| [[Dorset Park]]\n| 2004,<br />2010\n|\n* <small>'''Chapel''' - Old Age Home</small>\n* <small>May 10, 2010 - [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity#Consecration of a church|Consecration of Chapel]].</small>\n|\n|-\n| The Three Hierarchs Greek Orthodox Chapel \n| [[Don Mills]]\n| \n|\n* <small>'''Chapel''' - Metamorphosis Greek Orthodox School</small>\n|\n|}\n\n====Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada (UOCC)====\n{{main|Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada}}\n''(Diocese: Toronto and the Eastern Eparchy)''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| [[St. Volodymyr's Ukrainian Orthodox Cathedral (Toronto)]]\n| [[Kensington Market]]\n| \n1926{{#tag:ref|At a meeting, held at the Ukrainian Peoples\u2019 Home on October 31, 1926, the decision was made to lay the foundation for the parish.<ref name=\"St. Volodymyr\">[http://www.stvolodymyr.ca/AboutUs.html St. Volodymyr Ukrainian Orthodox Cathedral]. Accessed 2010-09-16.</ref>|group=note}}<br />\n1935{{#tag:ref|In 1935, the congregation bought the site at 400 Bathurst St. on which to erect a church. But for their immediate needs, the Congregation acquired a large building at 404 Bathurst.<ref name=\"St. Volodymyr\"/>|group=note}}<br />\n1948{{#tag:ref|The new church was officially opened and named St. Vladimir\u2019s Church.<ref name=\"St. Volodymyr\"/>|group=note}}\n|\n* <small>1951 The church was chosen as the see for the ruling [[Archbishop of Toronto and Eastern Canada]], and was elevated to the rank of a Cathedral.</small>\n* <small>1952 The Iconostasis of the Cathedral was installed, designed by the architect G. Kodak; the icons were painted by three artists \u2014 W. Balas, M. Dmytrenko, and I. Kubarsky, assisted by Petro Sydorenko, in the \u2018[[Ukrainian Baroque|Cossack Baroque]]\u2019 style, which is traditional and typical of the interiors in many Ukrainian churches.</small>\n* <small>1988 As part of the celebration of the [[Christianization of Kievan Rus'|Millennium of Christianity in Ukraine]], the cathedral was renamed St. Volodymyr Ukrainian Orthodox Cathedral.</small>\n* <small>Showcased in the annual [[Doors Open Toronto]] event, 2004.</small>\n| [[File:St Volodymyr's (Toronto).JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St . Andrew Parish\n| [[Dovercourt-Wallace Emerson-Junction]]\n| 1950<ref name=\"Gregorovich\"/>\n| \n| [[File:St . Andrew Parish, Toronto.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. Demetrius Sobor\n| [[Long Branch, Toronto]]\n| 1958<ref name=\"Gregorovich\">Andrew Gregorovich. ''[http://www.tgmag.ca/magic/mt54.html The Ukrainian Community in Toronto from World War One to 1971] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812042733/http://www.tgmag.ca/magic/mt54.html |date=2007-08-12 }}.'' Multicultural History Society of Ontario, 1984.</ref>\n| \n| [[File:LongBranchStDemetriusOrthodoxChurch.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| Ukrainian Orthodox Church of St. Anne\n| [[Highland Creek, Toronto]]\n| 1958<ref>[http://www.stannesorthodox.com Ukrainian Orthodox Church of St. Anne]. Retrieved 2011-12-06.</ref>\n|\n|\n|}\n\n====American Carpatho-Russian Orthodox Diocese (ACROD)====\n{{main|American Carpatho-Russian Orthodox Diocese}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| St. Euphrosynia of Polotsk Belarusian-Greek Orthodox Church\n| [[Dovercourt-Wallace Emerson-Junction]]\n| 1950,<br />1953,<br />1957<ref name=\"Sadouski\">John Sadouski. ''[http://kamunikat.fontel.net/www/knizki/historia/sadouski/06.htm \u041a\u0410\u041c\u0423\u041d\u0406\u041a\u0410\u0422\u0423: A History of the Byelorussians in Canada].''</ref>\n|\n*\n* <small>1950 The first Liturgy and prayers were held at the first location, on 23 March. Fr. Mikhail Mihai celebrated the Liturgy, a Greek Orthodox priest of Belarusian origin.</small>\n* <small>1952 In October the Parish was officially recognized by the Ecumenical Patriarch's Exarch for North America.</small>\n* <small>1953 The Parish, supported by the Belarusian National Association in Canada (BNA) bought a five-room house at 11 Cunningham Avenue. On 28 June the first Liturgy was celebrated there.</small>\n* <small>1957 First Liturgy in the new church at 1008 Dovercourt Rd (bought in 1956) is celebrated on 4 August 1957, under Very Rev. V. Sahaidakivskyi.</small>\n* <small>1966 Church was renovated and a church hall was built. Fr. V. Sahaidakivskyi supervised the acquisition of nearly twenty icons from the Iablochynski Belarusian Greek Orthodox Monastery in the western [[Belastok Region]].</small>\n* <small>1970 Parish celebrated 20th anniversary on 31 May, with Greek Orthodox Bishop Theodosius celebrating with Archimandrite I. Strok, the parish priest and four other Greek Orthodox priests. </small>\n* <small>1975 Parish celebrated 25th anniversary on 12 October, with Greek Orthodox Bishop Sotirios in attendance with the Very Rev. P. Veliki, parish priest.</small>\n* <small>2008 Church is transferred from Greek-Orthodox Diocese of Toronto to the American Carpatho-Russian Orthodox Diocese.</small>\n|[[File:St. Euphrosynia of Polotsk Belarusian-Greek Church.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| St. John the Compassionate Mission\n| [[Riverdale, Toronto]]\n| 1986<br>2001\n| \n* <small>'''Mission / [[Apostolate]]'''</small>\n* <small>In 1986, St. John the Compassionate Mission was erected as mission-parish of the Ukrainian Catholic church by Bishop [[Isidore Borecky]], to serve any one in the city in need of spiritual or material help.</small>\n* <small>In 2001, under Bishop [[Cornelius Pasichny]], it was released and received by Metropolitan [[Nicholas (Smisko)]] as an Apostolate of the Carpatho-Russian Diocese of the Ecumenical Patriarchate.</small>\n* <small>It serves all ages and all people in need regardless of background. Youth Summer camps are operated by the mission in co-operation with St Mary of Egypt Refuge. All services at the mission are offered in English. Its doors are open six day a week.<ref>''[http://stjohnsmission.org/ St. John the Compassionate Mission].'' St. John the Compassionate Mission. Retrieved: 13 November 2018.</ref></small>\n|\n|-\n| St. Silouan The Athonite Orthodox Church\n| [[Regent Park]] / [[Riverdale, Toronto]]\n| 2002\n| \n* <small>'''English / Multicultural Parish''' with over 9 languages spoken</small> <ref name=\":0\" />\n*<small>Operates liturgical worship, hospitality program to those in need in the local community, educational programs, child education (Montessori based Cateishm of the Good Shephard), youth and family programs.<ref name=\":0\">''[http://www.stsilouan.ca/ Welcome].'' St. Silouan the Athonite Orthodox Church. Retrieved: 11 December 2019.</ref></small>\n*<small>Colocated and partnered with St. John the Compassionate Mission until 2018.</small> \n*<small>Since 2018, it is located on the lower level of St. Cyril & Methody Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Cathedral.</small><ref name=\":0\" />\n|[[File:St Silouan Group Photo.jpg|alt=St Silouan parish community group photo|center|110x110px]]\n|-\n| St. Zoticos Orthodox Mission\n| [[Scarborough Village]]\n| 2018<ref name=Zoticus>''[http://stzoticos.org/ St. Zoticos - Mission Parish].'' St. Zoticus Orthodox Church. Retrieved: 30 October 2018.</ref>\n| \n*<small>Along with '''Scarborough Good Neighbours Drop In''', it seeks to live out in the everyday the beauty of the gospel. We are centered on the liturgy as the presence of Christ among the people of Scarborough. All services are mostly in English  <ref name=\"Zoticus\" /></small>\n*<small>Ministry of St John the Compassionate Mission in Toronto</small>\n*<small>English / Multicultural.</small> \n|\n|}\n\n===Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Diocese of the USA, Canada, and Australia===\n{{main|Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Diocese of the USA, Canada and Australia}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| St. Cyril & Methody Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Cathedral\n| [[Regent Park]]\n| 1910,<br />1948<ref>''[http://www.scmcathedral.com/history_E.html History].'' Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Cathedral Sts. Cyril and Methody.</ref>\n|\n* <small>Founded by [[Macedonian Bulgarians|Macedonian]] and [[Bulgarian people|Bulgarian]] immigrants, the church was originally located on Front St. and Eastern Ave.</small>\n* <small>[[May 24 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|May 24]] 1911, Consecration of the Church by Russian Abp. [[orthodoxwiki:Platon (Rozhdestvensky) of New York|Platon (Rozhdestvensky) of New York]] and Hieromonak Theophilact.</small>\n* <small>May 24, 1948, Laying of the cornerstone of the new Church on Sackville Street.</small>\n* <small>2010 Cathedral celebrated its Centennial Jubilee.</small>\n| [[File:St Cyril Orthodox.jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| St. George Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church\n| [[Regent Park]]\n| 1941\n| \n* <small>Founded by Macedonian immigrants as a result of a dispute with the parish of St. Cyril & Methody Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Cathedral</small>\n* <small>This church was part of the Orthodox Church of America until 2011 when its parish voted in favor of joining the Bulgarian Orthodox Church</small>\n|\n|-\n| Holy Trinity Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church\n| [[East Danforth]] \n| 1972<ref name=MAGOCSI291>Paul R. Magocsi, Multicultural History Society of Ontario. ''Encyclopedia of Canada's Peoples.'' Toronto: University of Toronto Press, 1999. p.291.</ref>{{#tag:ref|\"In 1972 the Sveta Troica (Holy Trinity) Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church was established in Toronto, mostly for political reasons. Many members belonged to the Bulgarian National Front (BNF) and the Macedonian Patriotic Organization (MPO) and firmly believe that Slavic Macedonians are part of the Bulgarian nationality. The parish was initially within the Bulgarian diocese of the Orthodox Church in America, during the late 1970s within the [[Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia|Russian Church Abroad]], and since 1982 under the [[Bulgarian Orthodox Church|Holy Synod in Bulgaria]]. It has about 150 members and is strongly committed to promoting Bulgarian identity and language.\"<ref name=MAGOCSI291/>|group=note}}\n|\n* <small>1973-1981 Father Vassil Mihailoff was the parish priest of Holy Trinity until his death in 1981.<ref name=HTMBEOC>''[http://ourholytrinitymbc.com/history.html Holy Trinity Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church].'' Holy Trinity Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church. Retrieved: 2013-06-20.</ref></small>\n* <small>1976 The church structure at 201 Monarch Park Ave, which was previously the ''Anglican Church of the Nativity'', was purchased from the Anglican Church in Canada.<ref name=HTMBEOC/></small>\n* <small>1988 An Ontario Supreme Court judge ruled that the church had been \"wrongfully operated\" for more than six years by the Synod of the [[Bulgarian Orthodox Church|Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church]] in Sofia, when it should properly have been under the jurisdiction of the \"[[Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia|Church in Exile]].\"<ref>Christine Harmanac. ''\"Priest Ousted as Judge Rules on Jurisdiction of Riven Church.\"'' [[The Globe and Mail]]. Monday June 27, 1988. Page: A13.</ref></small>\n* <small>1996 Large reproductions of frescoes with scenes from Bulgarian religious history were commissioned.<ref name=HTMBEOC/></small>\n* <small>2007-2013 Major renovations of the church hall and facilities were undertaken.<ref name=HTMBEOC/></small>\n| [[File:Holy Trinity Macedono-Bulgarian Eastern Orthodox Church.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Orthodox Church in America (OCA)===\n{{main|Orthodox Church in America}}\n\n====OCA - Archdiocese of Canada====\n{{main|Orthodox Church in America Archdiocese of Canada}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Christ the Savior Russian Orthodox Church\n| [[Seaton Village]]\n| 1915,<br />1930,<br />1966<ref name=\"Handera\"/>\n|\n* <small>Both Slavonic and English Services for primarily Russian community</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sobortoronto.com/?page_id=459&lang=en|title=Russian Orthodox Christ the Saviour Cathedral|last=Cathedral|first=Russian Orthodox Christ The Saviour|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n*<small>1907 Church structure founded, designed by architect Robert Balmer McGiffin.<ref name=\"CYPRIAN-MANNING\">Rector of the Church of St. Mary Magdalene in Toronto. ''[http://lostanglicanchurches.wordpress.com/2012/04/27/st-cyprians-manning-avenue/ \u2014lostanglicanchurches].'' Retrieved: 2013-06-20.</ref></small>\n* <small>1907-1966 ''St. Cyprian's Anglican Church.''<ref name=CYPRIAN-MANNING/></small>\n* <small>1915 Christ the Saviour Russian Orthodox church is founded by the first Russian immigrants in Toronto, with the blessing of the North American Metropolia Abp. [[orthodoxwiki:Eudocimus (Meschersky) of Nizhny Novgorod|Evdokim (Meschersky)]].<ref name=CHRISTTHESAVIOUR-TO>''[http://www.sobortoronto.com/?q=en/node/141 History of our parish and our temple].'' Christ the Saviour Russian Orthodox Cathedral in Toronto. Sun, 07/18/2010 - 22:06 \u2014 Admin.</ref></small>\n* <small>1941 On March 9, 1941, Fr. John Diachina, one of the most remarkable priests in North America, was appointed a rector.<ref name=CHRISTTHESAVIOUR-TO/></small>\n* <small>1952 Christ the Saviour Church is raised to the rank of a '''[[w:Cathedral|Cathedral]]''' by the new bishop of Toronto and Canada Bp. [[orthodoxwiki:Nikon (de Greve) of Brooklyn|Nikon De Greve]].</small>\n* <small>1960 Funeral of [[Grand Duchess Olga Alexandrovna of Russia]] at this parish.<ref>Ian Vorres. ''Epilogue to Imperial Drama: Handful of Russian Soil on Casket.'' [[The Globe and Mail]], Toronto, Thursday December 1, 1960. Page 29.</ref></small>\n* <small>1966 On June 1 the parish of Christ the Saviour acquired the building on Manning Avenue, and on October 30 a [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity#Consecration of a church|solemn blessing sanctification]] of the temple was held by Metr. Irenaeus and the newly appointed Abp. of Canada [[orthodoxwiki:Sylvester (Haruns) of Montreal|Sylvester]], con-celebrating with a multitude of clergy.</small>\n* <small>Count [[George Ignatieff]], representative of Canada in the United Nations (1966-1969), and father of [[Michael Ignatieff]], a former Leader of the Liberal party of Canada, was a parishioner of Christ the Saviour Cathedral.<ref name=CHRISTTHESAVIOUR-TO/></small>\n* <small>2002-2011 Rector of the temple was Archpriest Oleg Kirillow, who had served for over 10 years in Moscow; Fr Oleg put a lot of effort into renovating the Church and growing the Parish and Church school.<ref name=CHRISTTHESAVIOUR-TO/></small>\n|\n|-\n| Holy Myrrhbearers Orthodox Mission\n|[[University of Toronto|University of Toronto, St George Campus]]\n| 2015\n|\n* <small>'''English Language Mission''' located on Campus</small> \n* <small>Affiliation with Orthodox School of Theology at Trinity College</small> \n* <small>Has Orthodox Burial Society and Lay Pastoral Visitation Program in addition to Campus Ministry</small>\n* <small>Worship:Trinity College Chapel</small>  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archdiocese.ca/community/holy-myrrhbearers-orthodox-mission-toronto|title=Holy Myrrhbearers Orthodox Mission, Toronto, ON|date=2016-05-23|website=Archdiocese of Canada|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n|[[File:Trinity chapel.jpg|alt=|133x133px]]\n|-\n| St. Astius Albanian Orthodox Mission\n| [[Riverdale, Toronto]]\n| 2003\n| *<small>Albanian Speaking Mission</small><br />* <small>Worship: Danforth Baptist Church (Danforth Ave. & Bowden St.)</small>\n| [[File:Danforth Baptist Church.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. Tikhon Podvoriye\n| [[Wexford, Toronto|Wilson Heights, Toronto]]\n| 2001\n|\n* <small>Russian/Slavonic Language  Parish</small>\n* <small>Transferred to Moscow Patriarch as a Representational Church</small><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orthodoxcanada.ca/Toronto_ON_Saint_Tikhon_of_Moscow_Russian_Orthodox_Representation_Church_2000|title=Toronto ON Saint Tikhon of Moscow Russian Orthodox Representation Church 2000 - Canadian Orthodox History Project|website=orthodoxcanada.ca|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><small><br /></small>\n| \n|-\n| St. Seraphim of Sarov Church\n| [[Richmond Hill, Ontario|Richmond Hill]]\n| 2000,<br />2006\n|<small>Russian/Slavonic Language Parish</small><small>Located in anciliar chapel of Saint Mary's Anglican Church</small>\n\n<small>Worship: 10030 Yonge St, Richmond Hill, ON L4C 1T8.</small> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://orthodoxcanada.ca/Richmond_Hill_ON_Saint_Seraphim_Orthodox_Church_2000|title=Richmond Hill ON Saint Seraphim Orthodox Church 2000 - Canadian Orthodox History Project|website=orthodoxcanada.ca|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n|\n|}\n\n====OCA - Romanian Episcopate====\n{{main|Orthodox Church in America Romanian Episcopate}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| St. George Church\n| [[Keelesdale-Eglinton West]]\n| 1954\n|\n| [[File:St. George Church, Romanian.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. John the Evangelist Mission\n| [[Bedford Park, Toronto]]\n| 1999\n| * <small>'''Mission'''</small><br />* <small>Worship: St Timothy's Anglican Church</small>\n| [[File:St Timothy Anglican Church, North Toronto.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia (ROCOR)===\n{{main|Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia}} \n:''(Diocese: The Montreal and Canada Diocese)''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Holy Trinity Cathedral\n| [[Grange Park (neighbourhood)|Grange Park]]\n| 1949,{{#tag:ref|On November 2, 1949 Archbishop [[orthodoxwiki:Joasaph of Edmonton|Joasaph of Edmonton]], representing the synod of bishops of the [[Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia|Russian Orthodox church outside of Russia]], appointed Father Mathew Andrushenko as rector of the new parish. Reminiscent of the early days of Christianity, the small community gathered in a rented loft above a laundry on Parliament Street near Queen. Here they brought beautiful icons and began holding services. The very first took place on December 15, 1949 with Father Mathew. Eleven people were present at that service.<ref name=\"Handera\"/>|group=note}}<br />1953,{{#tag:ref|A small church was built by the hands of the first parishioners on Richmond Street just west of Berkeley, in [[Cabbagetown, Toronto|Cabbagetown]]. It was begun in the autumn of 1952 and was consecrated on September 6, 1953 by [[Metropolitan Vitaly Ustinov|Archbishop Vitaly]].<ref name=\"Handera\">Vladimir I. Handera. ''[http://www.tgmag.ca/magic/mt46.html The Russian Orthodox Church in Toronto].'' Multicultural History Society of Ontario, 1984.</ref>|group=note}}<br />1966<ref name=MALIKOV>{{in lang|ru}} Vasily Petrovich Malikov. ''[http://holytrinity.ws/parish/  \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a].'' Holy Trinity Cathedral. 2010. Retrieved: 2013-06-21.</ref>\n| \n* <small>1922 The structure at 23 Henry Street was founded asBeth Jacob Synagogue<ref>[[Toronto Daily Star]]. ''Jewish Composer and Cantor.'' Wednesday August 23, 1922. Page 5.</ref> on Sunday August 20, 1922; the architect was Benjamin Brown (Brow), of Toronto.<ref>[[Toronto Daily Star]]. ''Proposed Beth Jacob Synagogue.'' Saturday November 13, 1920. Page A1 - Front Page. (''Image'').</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [http://www.byad.ca/ Beth Jacob Synagogue] was the first synagogue to be built by a Jewish architect in the city.<ref>Lesley Ciarula Taylor. ''The History at 21 Henry St.'' [[Toronto Star]]. Tuesday September 08, 2009.</ref> One of the founders of the synagogue was Samuel Tepperman (d. March 1, 1960).<ref>Deaths: Samuel Tepperman. ''Canadian Jewish Review.'' Vol. XLII, No. 24. March 11, 1960. Page 11.</ref>|group=note}}</small>\n* <small>1951 The parish has had about 50 families in 1951. By the end of 1952 there were about 70 parish families.<ref name=MALIKOV/></small>\n* <small>1966 In June, the parish bought the large synagogue at 23 Henry St and began a complete renovation of the structure, completed in the Spring of 1967.<ref name=MALIKOV/></small>\n* <small>1969 November 16, [[Consecrations in Eastern Christianity#Consecration of a church|consecration]] of the temple by Abp. [[Vitaly (Ustinov)|Vitaly]] of Montreal and Canada (later Metropolitan and First Hierarch of ROCOR).<ref name=MALIKOV/></small>\n* <small>1973 [http://app.toronto.ca/HeritagePreservation/details.do?folderRsn=2435235&propertyRsn=218123 Heritage Property] of the City of Toronto (June 20, 1973).<ref>''[http://app.toronto.ca/HeritagePreservation/details.do?folderRsn=2435235&propertyRsn=218123 Heritage Property Detail - 23 HENRY ST].'' City of Toronto. Retrieved: 2013-06-21.</ref></small>\n* <small>2008 October 26, [[Liturgy of Preparation#Hierarchical Liturgy|Hierarchical Liturgy]] with Bp. [[Hilarion Alfeyev]] of Vienna and Austria presiding.{{#tag:ref|Bishop [[Hilarion Alfeyev]] later became the Archbishop of Volokolamsk, and chairman of the Department of External Church Relations (DECR) of the [[Russian Orthodox Church]]).|group=note}}</small>\n* <small>2012 November 4, Mitred Protopresbyter Vladimir Malchenko is honoured with the [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal|Queen Elizabeth II Diamond 60th Jubilee Medal]], on behalf of the [[Governor General of Canada]], in recognition of his role as an eminent social and ecclesiastical figure who has greatly contributed to the life of the [[Russians in Canada|Russian community in Canada]].<ref>The Russian Orthodox Church Outside of Russia. ''[http://www.russianorthodoxchurch.ws/synod/eng2012/20121126_entoronto.html Protopriest Vladimir Malchenko Honored with a Government Award].'' November 26, 2012.</ref></small>\n* <small>2013 September 4\u20138, 2013, ceremonies were held dedicated to the 400th anniversary of the [[House of Romanov]]s, headed by Metropolitan [[Hilarion (Kapral)]] of Eastern America and New York, First Hierarch of the ROCOR.<ref>The Russian Orthodox Church Outside of Russia - News Archive. ''[http://www.synod.com/synod/eng2013/20130912_entoronto400yrs.html Celebrating the 400th Anniversary of the Romanov Dynasty].'' DIOCESE OF MONTREAL AND CANADA: September 12, 2013.</ref></small>\n* <small>2019 Holy Trinity Cathedral celebrated its 70th anniversary.<ref>''[http://www.synod.com/synod/eng2019/20191202_entoronto.html 70th-anniversary celebrations at Holy Trinity Cathedral in Toronto, Ontario, led by the First Hierarch].'' Synod of Bishops of the Russian Orthodox Church Outside of Russia. December 2, 2019.</ref></small>\n| [[File:Holy Trinity Cathedral, Toronto.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| Holy Resurrection Church\n| [[Oakwood-Vaughan]]\n| \n|\n| [[File:Holy Resurrection Church.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Patriarchal Representation of the Russian Orthodox Church in Toronto===\n{{main|Russian Orthodox Church in Canada}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Parish of St.Tikhon\n| [[Clanton Park, Toronto|Clanton Park]]\n| \n|\n* <small>From 1995-2009 the location at 275 Wilson Heights Blvd. belonged to the Old Calendarist Saint Joseph of Arimathea Orthodox Church.</small>\n| \n|}\n\n===Serbian Orthodox Diocese of Canada===\n{{main|Serbian Orthodox Church}} \n:''(Diocese: [[Serbian Orthodox Eparchy of Canada]])''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| [[Saint Sava Serbian Orthodox Church (Toronto)|Saint Sava Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n| [[Cabbagetown, Toronto]]\n| 1948\n|\n* <small>Bishop (Saint) [[Nikolaj Velimirovi\u0107]] blessed the Church Hall on September 5, 1954.<ref name=RIVER>St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Church. ''[http://www.svetisavatoronto.com/default.asp?id=2&pageid=12 Forming the Congregation and Building the Church on River Street].'' Retrieved: 2012-01-12.</ref></small>\n* <small>The Church was completed and consecrated on May 22, 1955 by Bishop Dionisije; [[Grand Duchess Olga Alexandrovna of Russia|Princess Olga]] (sister of Russian [[Nicholas II of Russia|Emperor Nicholas II]]) attended the celebration and banquet, donating an icon of St. [[Alexander Nevsky|Alexander Nevski]] made by her own hand.<ref name=\"RIVER\"/></small>\n| [[File:St. Sava Serbian Orthodox Church.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. Luke's Serbian Orthodox Mission \n| \n|\n| \n* <small>'''Mission'''</small>\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Romanian Orthodox Archdiocese in the Americas===\n{{main|Romanian Orthodox Archdiocese of America and Canada}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| All Saints Romanian Orthodox Church\n| [[Oakridge, Toronto]]\n|\n|\n| [[File:All Saints Romanian Orthodox Church, Toronto.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. Dumitru / Three Hierarchs Romanian Orthodox Mission\n| [[Don Valley Village]]\n|\n| \n* <small>'''Mission'''</small>\n|\n|-\n| Holy Cross Orthodox Monastery\n| [[Amesbury, Toronto]]\n| 2007.\n| \n* <small>'''Monastery'''</small>\n* <small>Currently uses an Anglican/Episcopalian rectory, with plans to establish themselves in the countryside outside of Toronto.</small>\n|\n|}\n\n===Georgian Orthodox Diocese of America and Canada===\n{{main|Georgian Orthodox Diocese of America and Canada}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Saint Iveron Icon of the Mother of God Georgian Orthodox Church\n| [[Wexford, Toronto]]\n| 2010\n| Worship: [[Church of St. Jude (Wexford)|St. Jude Anglican Church]]\n| \n|}\n\n==Non-Canonical Churches{{#tag:ref|Not members of the Canadian Conference of Orthodox Bishops.|group=note}}==\n\n===Old Calendar Jurisdictions{{#tag:ref|The [[Old Calendarists|Old Calendar]] schism occurred in 1935, when three bishops (''Germanos of Demetrias, the former Metropolitan of Florina, Chrysostom (Kavouridis), and Chrysostomos (Demetriou) of Zakynthos'') declared their separation from the official [[Church of Greece]] stating that the calendar change that had been implemented in 1924 was a [[Schism (religion)|schismatic]] act. Greek Old Calendarist groups maintain that they have not separated over a mere calendar, rather that the calendar is a symptom of what has been called \"the pan-heresy of [[ecumenism]].\"|group=note}}===\n\n====Metropolis of the Genuine Greek Orthodox Church (GOC) of America====\n{{main|Greek Old Calendarists}}\n:''('''Florinite''', 1937-)''<ref>GNISIOS. ''[http://gnisios.narod.ru/florinite.html The Florinite Synod].'' True Orthodox Christian Resources.</ref>\n:''(Holy Metropolis of Toronto, under Metropolitan Moses)''{{#tag:ref|See also:\n:*''[http://www.hotca.org/directory Parish Directory].'' Holy Metropolis of the G.O.C. of America.\n:*''[http://orthodoxyinfo.org/bishops.html NORTH AMERICAN EPARCHIAL SYNOD].'' Genuine Greek Orthodox Church of America (Toronto Church website).|group=note}}\n:* ''(A Metropolis of the '''Genuine Orthodox Church of Greece''', under Archbishop Kallinikos of Athens and All Greece (2010-present))''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Saint Nektarios Greek Orthodox Cathedral\n| [[Davenport, Toronto]]<br /><br />1223 Dovercourt Road, Toronto, Ontario M6H 2Y1 \n|\n|\n* <small>2011 Up until the Spring of 2011, this parish was part of the [[Holy Orthodox Church in North America]] (HOCNA), ''Metropolis of Toronto''.<ref name=CARRAS2011>Fr. Panagiotes Carras. ''[https://groups.yahoo.com/group/OrthodoxInfo/message/858 Metropolitan Moses and Bishop Sergius to be received into TOC of Greece Synod].'' Yahoo! Groups: OrthodoxInfo. Sat May 14, 2011 12:51 am.</ref></small>\n* <small>Services in Greek and English</small>\n|\n|-\n| Saint Joseph of Arimathea Orthodox Church \n| [[Pickering, Ontario|Pickering]]<br /><br />510 Whitevale Rd, Pickering, Ontario L0H 1M0 \n| 1985,<br />1995,<br />2010\n|\n* <small>2011 Up until the Spring of 2011, this parish was part of the [[Holy Orthodox Church in North America]] (HOCNA), ''Metropolis of Toronto''.<ref name=CARRAS2011/></small>\n* <small>Services in English</small>\n|\n|-\n| Orthodox Church of the Mother of God of Prusa \n| [[Corktown, Toronto]]<br /><br />461 Richmond Street E., Toronto, Ontario M5A 1R1 \n|\n|\n* <small>1953 The structure at 461 Richmond Street E. was founded in 1953 as the Holy Trinity Russian Orthodox Church ([[Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia|ROCOR]]), which later moved to 23 Henry St.</small>\n* <small>2011 Up until the Spring of 2011, this parish was part of the [[Holy Orthodox Church in North America]] (HOCNA), ''Metropolis of Toronto''.<ref name=CARRAS2011/></small>\n* <small>Services in Greek</small>\n| [[File:Orthodox Church of the Mother of God of Prusa.JPG|100px]]\n|-\n| St. Dunstan Orthodox Mission\n| [[Swansea, Toronto|Swansea]]<br /><br />360 Windermere Avenue, Toronto, Ontario M6S 3L4\n| \n|\n* <small>'''Mission'''</small>\n|\n|-\n| Greek Orthodox Church of the Holy Martyrs Raphael, Nicholas, and Irene\n| [[Old East York]]<br /><br />230 Glebemount Avenue Toronto, Ontario M4C 3T4\n|\n| \n* <small>2014 The [[Orthodox Church of Greece (Holy Synod in Resistance)|Holy Synod in Resistance]], of which this parish was a part (under the Archdiocese of Etna (California)), united itself to the Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece and formally ceased to exist.<ref name=RESISTANCE2014>Metropolitan Cyprian of Oropos and Phyle. ''[http://www.synodinresistance.org/pdfs/2014/03/20/20140320aAnnouncement.pdf Official Notification: Thursday of the Third Week of the Great Fast, March 7/20, 2014 - The Ecclesiastical Union of the (Church of the True Orthodox Christians and the Orthodox Community in Resistance)].'' March 7/20, 2014. 6 pp.</ref></small>\n| [[File:Greek Orthodox Church of the Holy Martyrs Raphael, Nicholas, and Irene (Toronto).jpg|100px]]\n|-\n| [[Saint Michael the Archangel Serbian Orthodox Church (Toronto)|Saint Michael the Archangel Serbian Orthodox Church]]\n| [[Dovercourt Park]]<br /><br />212 Delaware Avenue, Toronto, Ontario M6H 2T7 \n| 1964{{#tag:ref|Built in 1890, as a 19th century Anglican church, it has been the Serbian community's downtown-Toronto local church since the 1960s.<ref>Sander Gladstone Architect. ''[http://www.sga-architect.com/project_details.php?pid=11896392744871&fid=50 Projects: Serbian Eastern Orthodox Church].'' Toronto, Ontario, Canada, 2005.</ref>|group=note}}<br />2005{{#tag:ref|This was a recent architectural project (2002-2005), to partially demolish, totally renovate, and add to, an existing 500 sm, circa 1890, church, in order to create a 1,700 sm/18,000 sf, universally-accessible, barrier-free, 4-storey, single-aisled, basilica and community centre. Stylistically, the building synthesizes [[Architecture of Serbia|Serbian]] [[Byzantine architecture#Comnenian and Paleologan periods|late-Byzantine]] architectural-styles and icon styles. It has many copper domes, cupolas, and trim; and great lighting & wood panels.<ref>Archive Doors Open Toronto. 2008. ''[http://wx.toronto.ca/inter/culture/doorsopen2008.nsf/BuildingsAll/9B22BA29E9515C568525740D006162FC?OpenDocument Serbian Eastern Orthodox Church of St. Archangel Michael].</ref>|group=note}}<br />2010{{#tag:ref|As a result of an internal conflict ca.late 2009/early 2010, this parish was transferred out of the ''' ''Serbian Orthodox Diocese of Canada'' ''', and placed under the ''' ''[http://www.synodinresistance.org/Administration_en/Etna.html Archdiocese of Etna (California)]'' '''. The first Liturgy under the new jurisdiction was on Sunday April 11, 2010.|group=note}}<br />2014{{#tag:ref|Transfers to the Metropolis of the Genuine Greek Orthodox Church (GOC) of America.|group=note}}\n|\n* <small>1890 Church structure built as a 19th-century Anglican church.</small>\n* <small>2008 Showcased in the annual [[Doors Open Toronto]] event.</small>\n* <small>2014 The [[Orthodox Church of Greece (Holy Synod in Resistance)|Holy Synod in Resistance]], of which this parish was a part from 2010-2014 (under the Archdiocese of Etna (California)), united itself to the Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece and formally ceased to exist.<ref name=RESISTANCE2014/><ref>''[http://www.hotca.org/directory#toronto Parish Directory: Church of the GOC of America].'' The Church of the GOC of America. Last Updated on Tuesday, 31 March 2015 21:02. Retrieved: 15 July 2015.</ref></small>\n* <small>2014 The parish celebrated its 50th anniversary (1964-2014)</small>\n| [[File:St. Archangel Michael Serbian Orthodox Church.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n====True Orthodox Church of Greece (\"Makarian (Lamian) Synod\")====\n{{main|Greek Old Calendarists}}\n:''('''Florinite''', 1995-)''\n:''(True Orthodox Church of Greece under Archbishop Makarios of Athens and All Greece (2004-present))''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| St Kosmas Aitolos Greek Orthodox Church{{#tag:ref|See: ''[http://www.omologitis.org/?page_id=766&lang=en Parishes and Monasteries abroad].'' Confessor (Unofficial site).|group=note}}\n| [[O'Connor\u2013Parkview]]<br /><br />2815 St Clair Ave E., Toronto, ON  M4B 1N3\n|\n|\n* <small>Until 1995, this church was a part of the main Old Calendar (\"Florinite\") Church of Greece - the [[orthodoxwiki:Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece|Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece]] - under Archbishop [[Chrysostomos II Kioussis|Chrysostom (Kiousis)]] of Athens and All Greece (+2010).{{#tag:ref|In 1995, a resistance faction of six bishops formed within the Old Calendar Florinte Synod of Archbishop [[Chrysostomos II Kioussis|Chrysostom (Kiousis)]] ([[orthodoxwiki:Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece|Church of the Genuine Orthodox Christians of Greece]]) and '''separated itself''' over what they claimed to be a series of canonical infractions, headed by Metropolitan Kallinikos (Hatzis) of Lamia. By early 1997, the movement had fragmented into three groups, one of which reconciled with Archbishop Chrysostom (Kiousis). A second group, led by Paisios Loulourgas (Met. of America) and Vikentios Malamatenios (titular Bp. of Avlona), submitted to the Ecumenical Patriarchate (in 1998).<ref>[[Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of America|GREEK ORTHODOX ARCHDIOCESE OF AMERICA]]. ''[http://www.goarch.org/news/goa.news617 Archbishop Spyridon officially receives Metropolitan Paisios and Bishop Vikentios].'' Apr 23, 1998.</ref> Later in 1997, Kallinikos of Lamia and Euthymios of Thessaloniki proceeded to ordain five titular bishops in an attempt to create a new synod; in 2003, they finally decided to elect a primate, and elected Makarios (Kavakides) of Athens.|group=note}}</small>\n|[[File:2011-08-28 St Kosmas Aitolos Greek Orthodox Church Toronto (G.O.C. of Greece).jpg|100px]]\n|}\n\n====Matthewite True Orthodox Christians in the United States====\n{{main|Greek Old Calendarists}}\n:''('''Matthewite''')''{{#tag:ref|The first Primate of Athens selected by the Matthewites was Agathangelos of Athens in 1958, who reposed in 1967. His successor was Archbishop Andreas of Athens who was elected to the primacy in 1972, retiring in 2003 (+2005). In 2003 Archbishop Nicholas of Athens was elected, considered by many to have a progressive vision for the Matthewite church.|group=note}}\n:''(Genuine Orthodox Church of Greece, under Archbishop Nicholas of Athens and All Greece)''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| Church of the Exaltation of the Holy Cross\n| [[Scarborough Junction]]<br /><br />618 Birchmount Road, Toronto, Ontario M1K 1P9\n|\n| \n* <small>Matthewite Old Calendar Synod.</small>\n|\n|}\n\n===Unrecognized Independent Churches===\n\n====Macedonian Orthodox{{#tag:ref|In 1967 the [[Macedonian Orthodox Church \u2013 Ohrid Archbishopric|Church in Macedonia]] unilaterally declared its autocephaly from the [[Serbian Orthodox Church]], a move which is not recognised by any of the churches of the [[Orthodox Church organization|Eastern Orthodox Communion]], and since then, the Macedonian Orthodox Church is not in communion with any Orthodox Church.|group=note}}====\n{{main|American-Canadian Macedonian Orthodox Diocese}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| [[St. Clement of Ohrid Macedonian Orthodox Cathedral, Toronto|St. Clement of Ohrid Macedonian Orthodox Cathedral]]\n| [[Thorncliffe Park]]<br /><br />76 Overlea Blvd, Toronto, Ontario M4H 1C5 \n| 1964\n|\n| [[File:St. Clement of Ohrid Macedonian Orthodox Cathedral, Toronto.png|100px]]\n|}\n\n====Belarusian Autocephalous Orthodox Church====\n{{main|Belarusian Autocephalous Orthodox Church}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n!width=28%|Congregation\n!width=18%|Location\n!width=20%|Dates\n!width=35%|Notes\n!width=7%|Image\n|-\n| St. Cyril of Turov Parish\n| [[Dovercourt-Wallace Emerson-Junction]]<br /><br />524 St. Clarens Ave, Toronto, Ontario M6H 3W7\n| 1954,<br />1959<ref name=\"Sadouski\"/>\n|\n| [[File:St. Cyril of Turov Parish.JPG|100px]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Christianity|Canada}}\n'''Toronto Church Lists'''\n* [[List of Anglican churches in Toronto]]\n* [[List of Presbyterian churches in Toronto]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic churches in Toronto]]\n* [[List of United Church of Canada churches in Toronto]]\n* [[List of Synagogues in Toronto]]\n'''Other Church Lists'''\n* [[List of Coptic Orthodox Churches in Canada]] ''([[Non-Chalcedonianism|Non-Chalcedonian]])''\n* [[List of Greek Orthodox churches in the United States]]\n\n'''General'''\n* [[Byzantine Rite Christianity in Canada]]\n* [[Timeline of Eastern Orthodoxy in America]]\n* [[List of cemeteries in Toronto]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Eastern Orthodox Church footer|collapsed}}\n{{OCA dioceses|collapsed}}\n{{Toronto|collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Orthodox Churches In Toronto}}\n[[Category:Toronto-related lists|Churches, Orthodox]]\n[[Category:Churches in Toronto|Orthodox]]\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox church buildings in Canada|Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lists of churches in Canada|Toronto, Orthodox churches]]\n[[Category:Christianity in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy-related lists]]\n", "name_user": "Serbianboy87", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Orthodox_churches_in_Toronto"}
{"title_page": "Belle Yang", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n'''Belle Yang''' (born 1965) is an artist, author, [[Graphic novelists|graphic novelist]] and children's book writer.\n\nYang was born in [[Taiwan]] in 1965, and moved to the San Francisco Bay area with her parents when she was seven years old.<ref name=myrow2016>{{cite web|last1=Myrow|first1=Rachel|title=Crossing Cultures: The Compelling Tug of Chinese Memories on Belle Yang|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/10/14/crossing-cultures-the-compelling-tug-of-chinese-memories-on-belle-yang/|website=KQED Arts|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> She graduated from University of California, Santa Cruz with a degree in biology, then enrolled in art school. When an ex boyfriend began harassing Yang, her parents sent her to live with friends of the family in Beijing.<ref name=arana2007>{{cite web|last1=Arana|first1=Marie|title=Belle Yang|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802211.html|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=1 July 2007}}</ref> She spent three years in China, traveling the country and studying history and classical Chinese art. She was in Beijing during the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], and returned to the US later that year.<ref name=arana2007 /> Once home, she started recording her parents' stories of their life in China, and that led to her first book, ''Baba, A Return to China Upon My Father's Shoulders'', in 1994. The book, published by [[Harcourt, Brace & Co.|Harcourt Brace]], was about her father, Joseph Yang, walking out of a 1940s war-torn China.<ref name=myrow2016 />\n\nAuthor [[Amy Tan]], who wrote the foreword to ''Baba'', says that \"Belle Yang is an American writer who writes in English and thinks in Chinese\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beason|first1=Tyrone|title=Artist, author Belle Yang crafts tales of immigrants\u2019 hopes, hardships|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/artist-author-belle-yang-crafts-tales-of-immigrants-hopes-hardships/|website=The Seattle Times|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=December 10, 2004}}</ref> [[Maxine Hong Kingston]] compared Yang's art and writing to that of [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]] and [[Marc Chagall]].<ref name=arana2007 /> The [[Kirkus Reviews|''Kirkus Review'']] wrote that \"Yang's work is like a lovely painted scroll swimming with wild souls, beasts, birds, flowers, day and night sky, tragedy, and hope\".<ref>{{cite web|title=BABA by Belle Yang|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/belle-yang/baba/|website=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Yang wrote a second book about her father's exodus from China, ''Odyssey of a Manchurian''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Odyssey of a Manchurian by Belle Yang|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/belle-yang-5/the-odyssey-of-a-manchurian-2/|website=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> She completed the trilogy, in 2010, with publication by [[W. W. Norton & Company|W.W. Norton and Company]] of the graphic novel ''[[Forget Sorrow, An Ancestral Tale]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Forget Sorrow {{!}} W. W. Norton & Company|url=http://books.wwnorton.com/books/Forget-Sorrow/|website=books.wwnorton.com|accessdate=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYang has also written children's books including ''Chili-Chili-Chin-Chin'', ''Foo the Flying Frog of Washtub Pond'', ''Always Come Home to Me'' and ''My Name Is Hannah'', a retelling of her family waiting for its [[Green card workers|green card]] after entering the United States.\n\nYang has had numerous museum exhibitions, including a national tour in its third year, ''Crossing Cultures: Belle Yang, A Story of Immigration''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Crossing Cultures: Belle Yang,  A Story of Immigration\" chronicling the journey of California-based  artist & author opens May 20 - California Museum|url=http://www.californiamuseum.org/press-release/crossing-cultures-belle-yang-story-immigration-chronicling-journey-california-based|website=www.californiamuseum.org|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> She is the subject of a film documentary by Mac and Ava Motion Pictures that has been telecast on [[public television]], ''My Name Is Belle''.<ref name=arana2007 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/living/article/IMMIGRANT-STORIES-Film-profiles-artist-and-2592997.php|title=IMMIGRANT STORIES / Film profiles artist and writer who mines family's past in China|last=Maddan|first=Heather|last2=Writer|first2=Chronicle Staff|date=2007-05-20|website=SFGate|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Baba : a return to China upon my father's shoulders|date=1996|publisher=Harcourt Brace|location=New York|isbn=9780156002394|edition=1st Harvest Book|url=https://archive.org/details/babareturntochin00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=The odyssey of a Manchurian|date=1996|publisher=Harcourt Brace|location=New York|isbn=9780151001750|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/details/odysseyofmanchur00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Chili-chili-chin-chin|date=1999|publisher=Silver Whistle|location=San Diego, Calif.|isbn=978-0152020064|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/chilichilichinch0000yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Hannah is my name|date=2004|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Cambridge, Mass.|isbn=9780763622237|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Always come home to me|url=https://archive.org/details/alwayscomehometo0000yang|url-access=registration|date=2007|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=9780763628994|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Foo, the flying frog of Washtub Pond|date=2009|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763636159|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Forget sorrow : an ancestral tale|date=2010|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=9780393068344|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/details/forgetsorrowance00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=A nest in springtime : a bilingual book of numbers = Chun tian de niao chao|date=2012|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763652791|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Summertime rainbow : a bilingual book of colors = Xia tian de cai hong|date=2012|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763652807|edition=1st}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yang, Belle}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American writers of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women artists]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese graphic novelists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz alumni]]\n[[Category:Female comics writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=March 2017}}\n\n'''Belle Yang''' (born 1965) is an artist, author, [[Graphic novelists|graphic novelist]] and children's book writer.\n\nYang was born in [[Taiwan]] in 1965, and moved to the San Francisco Bay area with her parents when she was seven years old.<ref name=myrow2016>{{cite web|last1=Myrow|first1=Rachel|title=Crossing Cultures: The Compelling Tug of Chinese Memories on Belle Yang|url=https://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/10/14/crossing-cultures-the-compelling-tug-of-chinese-memories-on-belle-yang/|website=KQED Arts|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us|date=October 14, 2016}}</ref> She graduated from University of California, Santa Cruz with a degree in biology, then enrolled in art school. When an ex boyfriend began harrassing Yang, her parents sent her to live with friends of the family in Beijing.<ref name=arana2007>{{cite web|last1=Arana|first1=Marie|title=Belle Yang|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/06/28/AR2007062802211.html|website=The Washington Post|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=1 July 2007}}</ref> She spent three years in China, traveling the country and studying history and classical Chinese art. She was in Beijing during the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests]], and returned to the US later that year.<ref name=arana2007 /> Once home, she started recording her parents' stories of their life in China, and that led to her first book, ''Baba, A Return to China Upon My Father's Shoulders'', in 1994. The book, published by [[Harcourt, Brace & Co.|Harcourt Brace]], was about her father, Joseph Yang, walking out of a 1940s war-torn China.<ref name=myrow2016 />\n\nAuthor [[Amy Tan]], who wrote the foreword to ''Baba'', says that \"Belle Yang is an American writer who writes in English and thinks in Chinese\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Beason|first1=Tyrone|title=Artist, author Belle Yang crafts tales of immigrants\u2019 hopes, hardships|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/artist-author-belle-yang-crafts-tales-of-immigrants-hopes-hardships/|website=The Seattle Times|accessdate=May 15, 2017|date=December 10, 2004}}</ref> [[Maxine Hong Kingston]] compared Yang's art and writing to that of [[Isaac Bashevis Singer]] and [[Marc Chagall]].<ref name=arana2007 /> The [[Kirkus Reviews|''Kirkus Review'']] wrote that \"Yang's work is like a lovely painted scroll swimming with wild souls, beasts, birds, flowers, day and night sky, tragedy, and hope\".<ref>{{cite web|title=BABA by Belle Yang|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/belle-yang/baba/|website=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Yang wrote a second book about her father's exodus from China, ''Odyssey of a Manchurian''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Odyssey of a Manchurian by Belle Yang|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/belle-yang-5/the-odyssey-of-a-manchurian-2/|website=Kirkus Reviews|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> She completed the trilogy, in 2010, with publication by [[W. W. Norton & Company|W.W. Norton and Company]] of the graphic novel ''[[Forget Sorrow, An Ancestral Tale]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Forget Sorrow {{!}} W. W. Norton & Company|url=http://books.wwnorton.com/books/Forget-Sorrow/|website=books.wwnorton.com|accessdate=May 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYang has also written children's books including ''Chili-Chili-Chin-Chin'', ''Foo the Flying Frog of Washtub Pond'', ''Always Come Home to Me'' and ''My Name Is Hannah'', a retelling of her family waiting for its [[Green card workers|green card]] after entering the United States.\n\nYang has had numerous museum exhibitions, including a national tour in its third year, ''Crossing Cultures: Belle Yang, A Story of Immigration''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Crossing Cultures: Belle Yang,  A Story of Immigration\" chronicling the journey of California-based  artist & author opens May 20 - California Museum|url=http://www.californiamuseum.org/press-release/crossing-cultures-belle-yang-story-immigration-chronicling-journey-california-based|website=www.californiamuseum.org|accessdate=May 15, 2017|language=en}}</ref> She is the subject of a film documentary by Mac and Ava Motion Pictures that has been telecast on [[public television]], ''My Name Is Belle''.<ref name=arana2007 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/living/article/IMMIGRANT-STORIES-Film-profiles-artist-and-2592997.php|title=IMMIGRANT STORIES / Film profiles artist and writer who mines family's past in China|last=Maddan|first=Heather|last2=Writer|first2=Chronicle Staff|date=2007-05-20|website=SFGate|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Baba : a return to China upon my father's shoulders|date=1996|publisher=Harcourt Brace|location=New York|isbn=9780156002394|edition=1st Harvest Book|url=https://archive.org/details/babareturntochin00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=The odyssey of a Manchurian|date=1996|publisher=Harcourt Brace|location=New York|isbn=9780151001750|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/details/odysseyofmanchur00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Chili-chili-chin-chin|date=1999|publisher=Silver Whistle|location=San Diego, Calif.|isbn=978-0152020064|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/chilichilichinch0000yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Hannah is my name|date=2004|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Cambridge, Mass.|isbn=9780763622237|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Always come home to me|url=https://archive.org/details/alwayscomehometo0000yang|url-access=registration|date=2007|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=9780763628994|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Foo, the flying frog of Washtub Pond|date=2009|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763636159|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Forget sorrow : an ancestral tale|date=2010|publisher=W.W. Norton|location=New York|isbn=9780393068344|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/details/forgetsorrowance00yang}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=A nest in springtime : a bilingual book of numbers = Chun tian de niao chao|date=2012|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763652791|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Yang|first1=Belle|title=Summertime rainbow : a bilingual book of colors = Xia tian de cai hong|date=2012|publisher=Candlewick Press|location=Somerville, Mass.|isbn=9780763652807|edition=1st}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yang, Belle}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American writers of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Taiwanese descent]]\n[[Category:American women artists]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese graphic novelists]]\n[[Category:University of California, Santa Cruz alumni]]\